body:
Connecting to a new device using the websocket URL shows this warning:

![Screen Shot 2022-03-01 at 1 10 32 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1145719/156249447-ec5948ad-dabc-4744-8360-6a116c1c0427.png)

comment_data.body: (I got this warning because I disconnected from the device, relaunched, and entered the websocket url, not because I launched from pub)
how did you originally launch DevTools? This warning should have only been enabled in the version shipped on pub. And what version of DevTools are you using?
What version of the Flutter IntelliJ plugin are you on? cc @helin24 Also, what version of DevTools (click the "i" icon in the top right)?

I'm using the 65.0.3 version of the Flutter plugin, but I see that 65.0.3 is available now. I'm using DevTools 2.9.4:
![Screen Shot 2022-03-01 at 2 44 41 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1145719/156261590-c0c255b4-3acf-40ae-bb13-9f1e291e6e34.png)
I also see the same message after upgrading the Flutter plugin to version 65.0.3

I believe this is dependent on the version of flutter only; the version of the IJ plugin shouldn't matter. I suppose this is an uncommon use case for DevTools from IJ, since typically users will open a new instance of DevTools for each app run. But seems strange that it's okay(?) for pub opening initially (I believe daemon->devtools.start calls dart devtools internally? if not we need to modify IJ) while connecting to a new websocket is not okay.
@johnpryan can you post the output of `flutter --version`? Also, can you try running `dart devtools` and tell me which version of DevTools launches that way?

```
flutter --version
Flutter 2.10.2 • channel stable • https://github.com/flutter/flutter.git
Framework • revision 097d3313d8 (11 days ago) • 2022-02-18 19:33:08 -0600
Engine • revision a83ed0e5e3
Tools • Dart 2.16.1 • DevTools 2.9.2
```

I see DevTools 2.9.2+1 when I run `dart devtools`

If that's the case then your IntelliJ plugin is still launching from pub. @helin24 2.9.4 was never pushed into the Dart SDK. It's either that, or an issue with Chrome where it is aggressively caching. John can you try to launch DevTools from IntelliJ and then copy the url into firefox or safari? If you are still seeing 2.9.4, then IntelliJ is definitely still using pub.
That seems to be what's happening. I see 2.9.2+1 when I open DevTools from VSCode.

We changed back to pub here: https://github.com/flutter/flutter-intellij/pull/5851

Maybe because starting the flutter tools daemon has some risk of failing and we don't want to wait for it? I think we'll either start the daemon later or accept using divergent methods for starting devtools for internal and external users.

rename.from: Entering a websocket URL shows warning

title: IntelliJ plugin launches from pub
